    # EXAMPLE 20: Antibiotic Resistance Patterns
    examples.append({
        "instruction": "You are the supply chain AI for MediCare Pharmaceuticals India. Analyze this public health-driven demand shift.",
        "input": "ICMR (Indian Council of Medical Research) report shows 60% antibiotic resistance to Amoxicillin and Ciprofloxacin in major Indian cities. Hospitals shifting prescriptions to Reserve antibiotics (Colistin, Vancomycin, Linezolid). Our Amoxicillin stock: 10M tablets. Reserve antibiotic stock: Near zero.",
        "output": "ANTIBIOTIC RESISTANCE - PORTFOLIO SHIFT REQUIRED\n\nPUBLIC HEALTH CONTEXT:\n- Antimicrobial Resistance (AMR): Growing global crisis\n- India: One of highest AMR burden countries\n- ICMR finding: 60% resistance to common antibiotics\n- Clinical implication: Doctors MUST switch to reserve antibiotics\n- Regulatory direction: WHO AWaRe framework adopted by India\n- Trend: Irreversible, accelerating\n\nPORTFOLIO IMPACT:\n- DECLINING (Access antibiotics - overused):\n  Amoxicillin: -60% demand (resistance makes ineffective)\n  Ciprofloxacin: -50% demand\n  Azithromycin: -40% demand\n\n- GROWING (Reserve antibiotics - last resort):\n  Vancomycin: +400% hospital demand\n  Linezolid: +350% demand\n  Colistin: +200% demand (controversial; niche)\n  Meropenem: +500% in ICUs\n  Tigecycline: +300%\n\nOUR INVENTORY CRISIS:\n- Amoxicillin: 10M tablets (90 days supply of declining product)\n- Reserve antibiotics: Near zero stock\n- Risk 1: Amoxicillin expiry/slow movement\n- Risk 2: Cannot supply hospitals needing Reserve antibiotics\n- Revenue risk: Hospitals will shift supplier to whoever has Reserve antibiotics\n\nACTIONS:\n\n1. IMMEDIATE PROCUREMENT - RESERVE ANTIBIOTICS:\n   - Vancomycin 500mg vials: Order 50,000 units\n     Supplier: Mylan, Sandoz, Sun Pharma\n     Cost: ₹600/vial × 50,000 = ₹3 crore\n   - Meropenem 1g vials: Order 30,000 units\n     Cost: ₹450/vial × 30,000 = ₹1.35 crore\n   - Linezolid 600mg: Order 20,000 tablets\n     Cost: ₹150/tablet × 20,000 = ₹30 lakh\n   - Total investment: ₹5 crore\n\n2. AMOXICILLIN DISPOSAL STRATEGY:\n   - 10M tablets at ₹2 = ₹2 crore inventory\n   - Shelf life check: How much time remaining?\n   - Option A: Rural market (lower antibiotic resistance in rural India)\n   - Option B: Export to markets with lower resistance (Africa, Southeast Asia)\n   - Option C: Sell quickly at 20% discount (recover ₹1.6 crore)\n   - Option D: Government health programs (rural prophylaxis)\n   - Reduce future Amoxicillin orders: Move to 15-day stock only\n\n3. HOSPITAL RELATIONSHIP INVESTMENT:\n   - Infection control committees: New decision makers (not just pharmacists)\n   - Key influencers: Hospital epidemiologists, ICU consultants\n   - Target: Present Reserve antibiotic availability to top 200 hospitals\n   - Medical reps: Retrain on Reserve antibiotic clinical positioning\n\n4. RESTRICTED CHANNEL FOR RESERVE ANTIBIOTICS:\n   - Colistin and Vancomycin: Hospital-only (not retail pharmacies)\n   - WHO AWaRe: Reserve antibiotics should be restricted\n   - Our policy: Sell only to hospitals with written protocol\n   - Protects: From misuse that creates further resistance\n   - Also protects us: From regulatory scrutiny\n\n5. STEWARDSHIP CONTRIBUTION:\n   - Partner: ICMR's Antimicrobial Stewardship Program\n   - Provide: Data on prescribing patterns from our sales data\n   - Build: Reputation as responsible distributor\n   - Differentiation: Not just selling, contributing to national health\n\nFINANCIAL:\n- Reserve antibiotic investment: ₹5 crore\n- Revenue from Reserve antibiotics: ₹8 crore (Year 1, growing 40% annually)\n- Margin: 15% = ₹1.2 crore\n- Amoxicillin write-down risk: ₹50 lakh (if moved aggressively at discount)\n- Net Year 1: +₹70 lakh\n- Year 3: Reserve antibiotics = ₹15 crore revenue, ₹2.25 crore profit\n\nUrgency: HIGH - Hospital prescriptions shifting NOW, cannot miss this transition"
    })

