    # EXAMPLE 22: Environmental Waste Disposal Regulations
    examples.append({
        "instruction": "You are the supply chain AI for MediCare Pharmaceuticals India. Analyze this compliance challenge.",
        "input": "New Biomedical Waste Management Rules 2023 require pharmaceutical distributors to accept drug returns from pharmacies and ensure proper disposal. Estimated: 500 tonnes of expired/returned drugs annually in our territory. New infrastructure and processes needed within 6 months. Non-compliance: ₹50 lakh fine + license suspension.",
        "output": "BIOMEDICAL WASTE COMPLIANCE - DRUG RETURN INFRASTRUCTURE\n\nREGULATORY REQUIREMENT:\n- New rule: Distributors responsible for pharmaceutical waste management\n- Scale: 500 tonnes/year in our territory\n- Infrastructure needed: Collection, storage, documentation, disposal\n- Timeline: 6 months\n- Penalty: ₹50 lakh + license suspension\n- Legal: CPCB (Central Pollution Control Board) enforcement\n\nWASTE CATEGORIES & HANDLING:\n- Expired tablets/capsules: Incineration or controlled landfill\n- Liquid medicines: Chemical treatment + disposal\n- Injectables: Special handling (sharps risk)\n- Controlled substances (NDPS): Witnessed destruction + NCB certificate\n- Cold chain drugs (vaccines): Specific protocols\n- Cytotoxic drugs (chemo): Specialized high-temperature incineration only\n\nCOMPLIANCE INFRASTRUCTURE:\n\n1. COLLECTION SYSTEM:\n   - Install: Return bins at all 3,500 pharmacy customers\n   - Bins: HDPE containers, labeled, lockable\n   - Cost: ₹2,000/bin × 3,500 = ₹70 lakh\n   - Collection frequency: Monthly pickup during regular delivery routes\n   - Process: Driver takes return bin, leaves empty replacement\n\n2. WAREHOUSE STORAGE:\n   - Dedicated waste room: Separate from usable inventory\n   - Segregation: By waste type (cytotoxic separate)\n   - Ventilation: For volatile compounds\n   - Security: Locked (prevent theft of controlled substance waste)\n   - CPCB approved: Storage area requirements\n   - Cost: ₹25 lakh warehouse modification\n\n3. DOCUMENTATION SYSTEM:\n   - Track: Each return by pharmacy, product, quantity, batch, reason\n   - Chain of custody: Pharmacy → us → disposal facility\n   - Records: Archived for 5 years (CPCB requirement)\n   - Certificate of destruction: For each disposal event\n   - Technology: Add waste module to existing ERP (₹15 lakh)\n\n4. DISPOSAL PARTNERSHIPS:\n   - Partner with CPCB-authorized disposal facility\n   - Options: Ramky Enviro Engineers, Clean India Ventures\n   - Contract: Annual disposal for 500 tonnes\n   - Cost: ₹3,000/tonne × 500 tonnes = ₹1.5 crore/year\n   - Cytotoxic: ₹15,000/tonne (specialized)\n\n5. CONTROLLED SUBSTANCE DESTRUCTION:\n   - NDPS waste: Destroy in presence of drug inspector\n   - Schedule: Quarterly destruction events\n   - Witness: Narcotics Control Bureau representative\n   - Certificate: Required from NCB for our records\n\nFINANCIAL MODEL:\n- Infrastructure investment: ₹1.3 crore (one-time)\n- Annual disposal cost: ₹2 crore/year\n- Staff: 3 dedicated waste management staff = ₹30 lakh/year\n- Total annual operating: ₹2.3 crore\n\nREVENUE OPPORTUNITY:\n- Charge pharmacies for return service: ₹500/pickup (monthly)\n- 3,500 pharmacies × ₹500 × 12 = ₹2.1 crore/year\n- Net cost to us: ₹2.3 crore - ₹2.1 crore = ₹20 lakh/year (minimal)\n- The service charge makes this nearly cost-neutral\n\nCOMPETITIVE ADVANTAGE:\n- Pharmacies prefer distributors who take returns\n- Reduces their compliance burden\n- Loyalty builder: Pharmacies stick with distributors who solve problems\n\nUrgency: HIGH - 6-month deadline, infrastructure requires 4-5 months to set up"
    })

