    # EXAMPLE 35: Competitor Pricing War
    examples.append({
        "instruction": "You are the supply chain AI for MediCare Pharmaceuticals India. Analyze this competitive pricing crisis.",
        "input": "New entrant distributor from Mumbai captures 15% of our market share in 6 months by undercutting prices 20%. Investigation reveals they're selling below cost to capture market. Our top 200 customers switched. Monthly revenue loss: ₹12 crore. How do we respond?",
        "output": "PREDATORY PRICING COMPETITION - STRATEGIC RESPONSE\n\nSITUATION ANALYSIS:\n- Competitor: Funded new entrant, loss-leader strategy\n- Market share lost: 15% of customers (200 accounts)\n- Revenue loss: ₹12 crore/month\n- Duration: 6 months (will they run out of money?)\n- Their strategy: Capture market share, raise prices once dominant\n\nROOT CAUSE INVESTIGATION:\n- Who is funding them? (Private equity, large distributor arm?)\n- How long can they sustain below-cost selling?\n- Which customers left? (Price-only buyers vs relationship buyers)\n- Why did our loyal customers leave? (Was price the only reason?)\n\nSTRATEGIC RESPONSE OPTIONS:\n\nOPTION 1: MATCH PRICES (Not Recommended):\n- Match their -20% pricing\n- Result: Both companies lose money\n- Winner: Whoever has deeper pockets\n- Risk: They have ₹500 crore VC backing; we don't\n- Risk: We destroy our own margins permanently\n- AVOID this option\n\nOPTION 2: HOLD PRICES, WIN ON SERVICE (Recommended Primary):\n- Don't engage in price war\n- Compete on dimensions they cannot easily match\n- Services: 4-hour emergency delivery, dedicated account managers\n- Technology: Real-time inventory visibility portal\n- Credit: Better payment terms for loyal customers\n- Win back: Relationship-oriented customers (50% of those who left)\n\nOPTION 3: SELECTIVE PRICE MATCH:\n- Identify: Which 200 accounts are most profitable?\n- For top 50 accounts only: Offer competitive pricing\n- Triage: Don't fight for unprofitable accounts (let competitor have them)\n- Focus resources: Win back profitable customers only\n\nOPTION 4: WAIT THEM OUT:\n- Calculate: How long can they sustain -20% pricing?\n- If they're burning ₹3 crore/month: Funding will run out\n- Typically: Funded new entrant has 12-18 month runway\n- Risk: If they have longer runway, market shifts permanently\n\nACTIONS:\n\n1. IMMEDIATE CUSTOMER RETENTION:\n   - Call top 100 accounts personally (MD/CEO level)\n   - Understand: Why did they leave? Only price?\n   - Offer: Service contract with SLA guarantees\n   - Provide: 3-year pricing lock (stability vs competitor uncertainty)\n   - Win back goal: 100 of 200 accounts within 90 days\n\n2. COMPETITIVE INTELLIGENCE:\n   - Map: Which suppliers does competitor source from?\n   - If they source from same manufacturers: Negotiate exclusivity\n   - Some manufacturers: Prefer fewer, larger distributors\n   - Approach: Top 5 manufacturers for preferred partner status\n\n3. DIFFERENTIATION INVESTMENT:\n   - Launch: 4-hour delivery guarantee (competitor can't match immediately)\n   - Invest: ₹2 crore in customer-facing technology\n   - Cold chain excellence: Certify temperature compliance publicly\n   - Relationship: Hospital meets, CME events, add value beyond drugs\n\n4. COST REDUCTION:\n   - While not matching competitor price: Reduce our costs\n   - Logistics optimization: 10% cost reduction\n   - Supplier consolidation: Better pricing from top 5 suppliers\n   - Pass savings: To at-risk customers (not all customers)\n   - Goal: Narrow price gap from 20% → 10%\n\n5. LEGAL OPTIONS:\n   - Check: If selling below cost violates Competition Act 2002\n   - CCI (Competition Commission of India): File predatory pricing complaint\n   - This won't stop them immediately but creates regulatory pressure\n   - Cost: ₹25 lakh for competition lawyer\n\nFINANCIAL MODEL:\n- Status quo (no action): Lose further ₹5 crore/month → ₹60 crore/year\n- Service investment: ₹5 crore\n- Win back 100 accounts: +₹6 crore/month\n- Competitor exits market (18 months): Full recovery\n- Net 18-month outcome: -₹30 crore (vs -₹108 crore do nothing)\n\nPSYCHOLOGY:\n- Stay calm: Price wars are won by staying disciplined, not reacting\n- Protect: Most valuable customers first\n- Accept: Some accounts are not worth fighting for\n\nUrgency: HIGH - Win back campaign must begin this week"
    })

